    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-11-17T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-11-17T04:00:00-05:00" n="414"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d414">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5151/968: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-11-17T16:00:00+07:00"
                            >November 17, 1943—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 5:23 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2184. For Secretary [of] Treasury from Adler.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Returned Chungking November 13.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Saw Dr. Kung same day and reported on Treasury’s attitude on future of
                        Board in accordance with Cairo instructions.<note n="94" xml:id="d414fn94"
                            >Mr. Morgenthau and Mr. White both were present at Cairo when Mr. Adler
                            was there for consultation.</note> He indicated it was perfectly
                        agreeable to him that Board should be wound up in near future. I suggested
                        it might be desirable for Treasury and Ministry to issue a joint statement
                        at suitable moment couched in appropriate language in order to avoid Axis
                        propaganda exploiting termination of agreement to which he readily
                        agreed.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Reference your 1638, November 13. Board should be able to meet its
                        obligations and settle outstanding business by December 31. In this
                        connection it is liquidation of sterling obligations which require most time
                        as our stabilization loan is still intact while sterling obligations under
                        Sino-British agreements of 1939 and ’41 will have to be handled.</item>
                </list>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed> [Adler] <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
